post_text:
Transportation Update:
- the school arrival times are 30 minutes later than last year, as a rule the bus stop will be 30 minutes later.
- bus times may be even later depending on the number of stops, with the A Day and B Day the number of riders varies.
-PM arrival times home depend on how long it takes to load the buses while we are only moving students one or two buses at a time, from classrooms, remaining six feet apart.
-AM Career and Tech (CTE) - there will be a bus at the MS-HS up near the tear drop to shuttle to BOCES. Bus will leave at 8:20. Either get dropped off of ride your normal bus. Transportation will be provided directly home from BOCES.
-PM CTE - Pick up at home will start at 11:05 am and then travel to BOCES, after CTE transportation will be provided home.

We appreciate everyone's understanding and patience as we work though these details.

post_text: CF Band Boosters have been sewing fabric covers for musical instruments as a way to enable our music students to safely play their instruments during the COVID-19 pandemic. District music teacher and band director Mr. Starr came up with the idea after seeing similar products for sale online that help mitigate aerosols that can be released when wind or brass instruments are played. Mr. Starr approached the Band Booster Club parents, who donated fabric and elastic and then got to work creating the covers. It was a true labor of love and a fantastic effort from our community, and Mr. Starr and his students are thrilled that the covers will keep the music playing at Chenango Forks!

post_text: During the COVID closure, CF's Spanish V and Costa Rica classes have been practicing their Spanish while learning about culture, immigration and more through Zoom calls. Several volunteers from across the Americas have given their time to meet with our students. Conversations were held with several teens and adults in Costa Rica, some local Spanish speakers including retired Spanish teacher Cheri Panko and local parent Maria Sweeney, as well as a former CF student, Elizabeth (Tiffany) Frazier who is currently working for the American Consulate in Monterrey, Mexico, and one of Elizabeth's coworkers who grew up in Mexico. Many thanks to the volunteers who took the time to help our students feel connected in this time of separation.

Many thanks to the volunteers who took the time to help our students feel connected in this time of separation.

post_text:
Chenango Forks Elementary School staff surprised School Principal Catherine Kacyvenski and Assistant Principal Hannah Elwyn with a parade of appreciation today! Led by several vehicles from the Chenango Bridge Fire Department, dozens and dozens of staff members drove their cars through the school district campus bus loop and past Ms. Kacyvenski and Ms. Elwyn, who were standing at the school’s flagpole. The two administrators had been asked to meet a few teachers at the flagpole at 3:15 p.m. -- though they didn’t know why -- and to their surprise, the parade ensued on their behalf!

The staff wanted to express their appreciation and gratitude to Ms. Kacyvenski and Ms. Elwyn for their extraordinary efforts during this challenging time.

Thank you, Ms. Kacyvenski and Ms. Elwyn!

post_text: On Saturday, May 16 at 8 p.m., the Council of Chief State School Officers is partnering with XQ Institute on "Graduate Together: America Honors the High School Class of 2020," a one-hour primetime show paying joyful tribute to high school seniors, their extraordinary teachers, and their families. This commercial-free special will air on ABC, CBS, FOX and NBC. During the show, high school seniors and other viewers will be invited to visit the Graduate Together website and click on their state to see specialized content for their graduating class. Students may visit the national website to submit photos, videos and speeches for a chance to be featured on the show. For more details, see the Graduate Together website: https://graduatetogether2020.com/

The Chenango Forks High School Art Department was selected by the U.S. Department of Education to provide designs for the NYS egg in the traditional White House Easter Egg Roll. Students Gianna Rullo and Julia Kurcin designed the final submissions, working under the guidance of art teacher Mr. Rosko. Gianna's design used an "I Love NY" theme, and Julia's design featured the NYC skyline.

Although the Easter Egg Roll event was canceled due to the coronavirus pandemic, the egg designs representing each state are being used in a virtual display that can be viewed here: https://www.flickr.com/photos/departmentofed/albums/72157713791602408/with/49757933646/

See Gianna's and Julia's NYS designs:

post_text: CFE 5th graders took a field trip to the Anderson Center at Binghamton University today for a concert presented by the Binghamton Youth Symphony Orchestra. This audition-only group of high school students put on an outstanding performance, and also demonstrated the various instruments of the orchestra. Dancers from The Dance Connection joined the orchestra for their closing number. 2020 marks the 20th year Mr. Allport has taken students to this concert, and or kids are always glad for the opportunity to experience a full orchestra performing live on stage.

post_text: Students in Mr. Niemiec's and Mr. Reid's Design and Drawing for Production classes built catapaults after learning about the physics of flight (trajectory, drag, propulsion, etc.) and the history of catapaults from the medieval ages to modern day uses. The students used scrap wood and fasteners, plus other materials they brought from home, to create their catapaults. The unit culminated in a contest for accuracy and distance as students launched their catapault and tried to hit a bucket 25 feet away. Watch video of launch: https://www.cforks.org/VideoUp/299dd704-1d56-42e4-8499-75d9535972c2.MP4.mp4

post_text: Congratulations to Brady Vaseleck, a fifth-grader at Chenango Forks Elementary who was recognized Friday as an "Akshar All-Star" by New York State Senator Fred Akshar. Senator Akshar joined CFE administrators, Superintendent Dr. Peck and Brady's parents for a surprise visit to his classroom, where he presented Brady with a framed certificate, t-shirt and challenge coin. Brady was selected by school administrators for his hard work in the classroom and the athletic field, and for his kindness and willingness to reach out to help others. Congratulations, Brady!

post_text:
Congratulations to the Chenango Forks Middle School Robotics team of Rudy Pavlik, Jack Vavra and Ryan Ferrara, who placed first in the VEX IQ Robotics competition Saturday at the Soule Road Middle School in Liverpool, NY. A total of 18 teams from schools throughout Central NY competed in the event, which challenged the students to problem solve through a game design challenge. After each team completed 8 matches, teams paired in two to work together as an alliance to score as many points as possible. The CF team won first place and will head to the state competition in February. Great job, boys!

(photo credit: Jen Pavlik)

post_text: On Dec. 8, the Chenango Forks Varsity cheerleaders earned a bid to compete in the UCA Cheerleading Nationals at Disney World in Orlando, Fl. These 20 girls created a routine in three short weeks of practice to compete in the regional level, where they received a bid to compete against other Varsity Large Squad teams. In the past year, the CF squad won a first-ever Winter STAC title, a D2 Large Squad Sectional title, placed 5th in the state competition, and won a first-ever STAC title in October. And now a bid to Nationals! Congratulations, girls!

post_text:
Mrs. Shoudy's 7th grade Family & Consumer Science classes recently held their first Cupcake Wars competition. The students collaborated to come up with creative flavor combinations and designs, working in teams to accomplish measuring accuracy and time management as they baked and decorated their cupcakes. They came up with some VERY creative ideas!

A panel of judges comprised of 7th grade teachers and members of the administration team had the tough but tasty task of determining the winners. The 3rd period class winner was a red velvet cupcake with vanilla pudding filling, cream cheese frosting and a fresh strawberry garnish. The winner of the 9th period competition was a chocolate cupcake with Oreo cookie buttercream frosting, garnished with mini Oreos. Other flavors included s'mores, Andies candy and fruity Pebbles cupcakes. Yum!

post_text: Tuesday, Nov. 5 was a Superintendent's Conference Day here at Chenango Forks. The agenda for the day focused on promoting a positive culture K-12, team-building and collaboration. Staff from all three buildings came together to participate in a day of idea sharing of curriculum and instruction, and unification K-12. Teachers and administrators were brought together in activities such as a group photo, ice breaker, grade level/department presentations and team trivia to meet different faces and make new friends from other buildings, to better communicate and collaborate more effectively and efficiently as a team to accomplish our focus for the day: Forks Nation, K-12 -- we are ALL in this together!

post_text: Several members of the Chenango Bridge Volunteer Fire Department, including CFE aide Kerri Hamilton, presented two fire safety assemblies Wednesday. CFE students learned about "Stop, Drop & Roll," and several got to practice it on stage. They were reminded about fire safety tips, and were encouraged to ask their parents about a family fire safety plan. They also had fun watching the firefighters race to put on all their firefighting gear! Thank you, Chenango Bridge firefighters, for taking the time to teach us the importance of fire safety!

post_text: Our librarian Ms. Slater has started a Library Buddy program that pairs each 5th grade student in Mr. Bender's and Mrs. Sanford's classes with a kindergarten student. The older students help the younger ones select a book, check out and then the students read together. This is a great opportunity for our 5th graders to take ownership of their library and show the younger ones how to use it, and it's a great introduction to the library for the kindergartners.

Dear Chenango Forks families,
This afternoon, our administration received a report from some concerned students about a statement made by another student that was perceived as a possible threat. This matter was immediately and thoroughly investigated by our administration and security personnel and we have determined that there is no credible threat to our school community. We appreciate and applaud our students who came forward. Thank you for your support.

post_text: A group of CFHS students were among approximately 600 students from area school districts who participated in the day-long Construction & Technology Career Day at the Broome County Highway Department facility in Chenango Bridge. The event gave students firsthand insight into careers in construction and technology fields, and even offered students the opportunity to operate heavy equipment such as bulldozers, backhoes and dump trucks under supervision.

post_text:
IMPORTANT NOTICE - Thursday, September 26, 2019
The Chenango Forks Middle School has been evacuated due to a gas odor that was detected this morning in the Family and Consumer Science classroom caused by a stove knob that was inadvertently turned on overnight. The room is currently being ventilated and local emergency services personnel have been contacted. As a precautionary measure, students and staff have been evacuated to the High School Auditorium until emergency personnel determine that it is safe to return.

post_text: Mr. Niemiec's Transportation class got an up-close look at a variety of different car engines when students, staff and visitors brought their cars to the construction parking lot for viewing. The most notable difference was how much simpler the engines are in older cars, such as the 1972 Chevy Nova. Much easier to make repairs on these cars, without all the complicated components of newer cars!

post_text: Members of the Chenango Forks High School Marching Band received the exciting news that they are invited to participate in the National Memorial Day Parade in Washington, D.C. on May 20, 2020. The parade will commemorate the 75th anniversary of the end of WWII. United States Congressman Anthony Brindisi submitted the band's nomination. The band will also have the opportunity to attend the offical National Memorial Day concert on the West Lawn of the U.S. Capitol and do some sightseeing during their D.C. visit. Congratulations to our talented marching band! Band director and music teacher Mr. Starr shared the news with band members as Superintendent Dr. Peck and Principal Hillis joined in to help celebrate.

post_text: Students in Mr. Niemiec's Tech 8 class are learning Computer Aided Drawing (CAD) through the AutoDESK Inventor program and using a 3D printer to bring their designs to life. Rachel Molstead designed & printed a 3D butterfly. Elijah Shephard designed a tool to move oven racks. As an extracurricular project, Nathan Atwater learned about stereolithography and gcode, which is used in computer-aided manufacturing. He learned to operate the 3D printing software & printer to create a Lego MegaFigure.

post_text: Basketball player and entertainer Ilze Luneau gave a dazzling show of ballhandling tricks at CFE recently. She dribbles, juggles and spins basketballs - even on a balance board - and her show includes motivational messages about setting goals, persevering and practicing kindness. post_text: Thank you for the feedback on our Facebook page. The CFCSD administrative team along with our SROs have reviewed the procedures for Lockouts, Lockdowns, and Shelter in Place. The district as well as local law enforcement believes the district did an excellent job with accessing the threat and ascertaining the information needed to deem the threat non-viable. It appears where the district may improve is a timelier parent notification. In the future, if a Lockout, Lockdown or a Shelter in Place occurs in the district, a call/text will be sent to ensure the safety of our students, staff and community. Mandated drills by New York State Education will not be followed with notification.

post_text: Students in Mrs. Q's Entrepreneurship & Marketing class had the opportunity to speak with Mr. Joseph E. Walsh, Jr., a Principal at Harkness, Dickey & Pierce, PLC in St. Louis, MO about patents and trademarks. Communicating via Facetime, Mr. Walsh was able to provide insight about the workings and legalities of both. Walsh is the brother of Mrs. Q. and has spoken as an expert in many trial cases and at the Supreme Court. It was a wonderful opportunity for the students to be able to connect their conversations to real-life situations.

post_text: LOCKOUT UPDATE: This morning, we received information that there had been a threat made to Chenango Forks High School. District Administration worked with law enforcement to investigate the threat, and it was determined that the threat was not credible. While the investigation was underway, from 8:27 to 8:55 a.m., all district buildings were in a lockout. No individuals were allowed to enter or leave. The lockout has ended, and normal school activity has resumed.

post_text:
"Super Cooper" Busch was known for making people smile, and that's just what he and his family did today at Chenango Forks Elementary School. Cooper won the hearts of people in our community as he bravely fought leukemia for 2 years. To commemorate the one-year anniversary of his becoming an angel in May 2018, Cooper's family gave CFE kindergarten classes -- and many other area kindergartens -- a gift of bubble machines, bubbles and popcorn, a few of the things Cooper loved. Each class also got a $20 gift card to use to pay it forward and make another class smile!
Visit the CFE website for lots more photos:https://www.cforks.org/protected/ArticleView.aspx?iid=5IAY0I&dasi=2GY

post_text: Eight CFHS seniors have earned the New York State Seal of Biliteracy and will receive distinction on their diploma at graduation. The Seal of Biliteracy recognizes high school graduates who have attained a high level of proficiency in listening, speaking, reading and writing in one or more languages in addition to English. Rigorous requirements, including the presentation of a culminating project, must be met to earn the seal. Congratulations to the following students for achieving this distinction: Josh Black, Julie Heaney, Declan Houlihan, Chaise Latsha, Loretta Wachter, Thomas Wachter for Spanish; Christopher Brewster for French, and Niklas Boeker for German.
